<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">
Adult habitus: Triocellate. General body colour pale, yellow to brown in alcohol. Head with large, quadrate, median dark brown marking covering frons and ocellar areas; compound eyes black, ocelli brownish with black rings, median ocellus paler; antennae and palpi light brown (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F7871724" captionText="Figure 1. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. Male A head and pronotum; B terminalia dorsal view; C terminalia ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681195" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">1</figureCitation>
A). Pronotum disc with brown median portion narrowly surrounded by elongate paler rugosities; sides paler (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F7871724" captionText="Figure 1. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. Male A head and pronotum; B terminalia dorsal view; C terminalia ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681195" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">1</figureCitation>
A). Mesonotum and metanotum have dark brown U-shaped markings (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F7871732" captionText="Figure 3. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. A male abdomen, dorsal view; B female abdomen, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681197" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">3</figureCitation>
A). Wings membrane transparent, legs pale. The anterior margin of abdominal tergum 1 brown, terga 2-7 have wide rectangular brown median stripe, tergum 8 has a small elliptical stripe anteromedially, lateral dark patches also being present on segments 1-4. Cerci pale brown, generally paler and covered with long setae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F7871732" captionText="Figure 3. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. A male abdomen, dorsal view; B female abdomen, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681197" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">3</figureCitation>
A).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" type="male">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">Male</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">
Body length 6.5-7.0 mm, forewing length 6.0-6.5 mm, hind-wing length 5.0-5.5 mm (n = 2). Tergum 9 paler, without any transverse process or modification (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F7871724" captionText="Figure 1. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. Male A head and pronotum; B terminalia dorsal view; C terminalia ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681195" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">1</figureCitation>
B). Tergum 10 with sclerotised dark brown shield in middle (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F7871724" captionText="Figure 1. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. Male A head and pronotum; B terminalia dorsal view; C terminalia ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681195" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">1</figureCitation>
B and Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F7871728" captionText="Figure 2. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. Male A terminalia lateral view; B epiproct dorsal view; C epiproct lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681196" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">2</figureCitation>
B). Sternum 9 ventrally with large trapezoidal subgenital plate, posterior margin truncate and extended over sternum 10 (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F7871724" captionText="Figure 1. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. Male A head and pronotum; B terminalia dorsal view; C terminalia ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681195" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">1</figureCitation>
C). Epiproct short and parallel from base to apex dorsally; apex swollen, shiny and rounded dorsally; lateral margins of epiproct from base to middle portion darker, medially brown (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F7871724" captionText="Figure 1. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. Male A head and pronotum; B terminalia dorsal view; C terminalia ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681195" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F7871728" captionText="Figure 2. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. Male A terminalia lateral view; B epiproct dorsal view; C epiproct lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681196" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">2</figureCitation>
); laterally, epiproct dark brown, broad at base then slightly tapered apically, apex swollen and slightly bent upwards (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F7871728" captionText="Figure 2. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. Male A terminalia lateral view; B epiproct dorsal view; C epiproct lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681196" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">2</figureCitation>
A-C).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" type="female">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">Female</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">
Body length 7.0-7.5 mm, forewing length 6.5-7.0 mm, hind-wing length 5.5-6.0 mm (n = 3). Habitus generally similar to male (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F7871736" captionText="Figure 4. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. Female A head and pronotum; B terminalia ventral view; C subgenital plate." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681198" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">4</figureCitation>
A). Abdominal terga 1-6 dorsally with rectangular stripes, tergum 7 with oval shape and tergum 8 with small rounded stripe anteromedially (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F7871732" captionText="Figure 3. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. A male abdomen, dorsal view; B female abdomen, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681197" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">3</figureCitation>
B). Posterior margins of sternum 8 bear large trapezoidal subgenital plate, covered with small hairs, reaching near posterior margins of sternum 9 and possess small rounded posteromedial notch. The sides of posterior notch covered with long fine hairs (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F7871736" captionText="Figure 4. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. Female A head and pronotum; B terminalia ventral view; C subgenital plate." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681198" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">4</figureCitation>
B-C).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">
The shape of the epiproct is characteristic of this new species. Epiproct short and almost parallel from base to apex dorsally, lateromedially sclerotised; apex swollen and rounded in dorsal view (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F7871728" captionText="Figure 2. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. Male A terminalia lateral view; B epiproct dorsal view; C epiproct lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681196" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">2</figureCitation>
B); in lateral view, epiproct parallel for its most part, except for swollen apex which is bent upwards (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F7871728" captionText="Figure 2. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. Male A terminalia lateral view; B epiproct dorsal view; C epiproct lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681196" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">2</figureCitation>
C).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">Etymology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">The species is named after the type locality, Liupan Mountain, also known by the Chinese name Liupanshan.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">China (Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region and Henan Province).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">
The new species pigmentation is mostly similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Sweltsa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sweltsa bicurvata" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicurvata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">Sweltsa bicurvata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Li, W. L" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" pagination="145 - 150" refId="B7871584" refString="Li, W. L, Wang, Y. Y, Li, W. H, Li, M. Y, 2021. Two new species of Sweltsa (Plecoptera: Chloroperlidae) from China. Zootaxa 5057 (1): 145 - 150" title="Two new species of Sweltsa (Plecoptera: Chloroperlidae) from China" volume="5057" year="2021">Li et al. 2021</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dong, Cui &amp; Weihai Li" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Sweltsa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sweltsa brevihamula" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevihamula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">Sweltsa brevihamula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Dong, W. B." journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" pagination="388 - 392" refId="B7871518" refString="Dong, W. B., Cui, J. X., Li, W. H., 2018. A new species of Sweltsa (Plecoptera: Chloroperlidae) from Sichuan Province of southwestern China. Zootaxa 4418 (4): 388 - 392" title="A new species of Sweltsa (Plecoptera: Chloroperlidae) from Sichuan Province of southwestern China" volume="4418" year="2018">Dong et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
), but these species possess a distinct sclerotised transverse ridge on tergum 9, while the new species lack that prominent morphological character. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stark &amp; Sivec" authorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Sweltsa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sweltsa wui" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wui">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">Sweltsa wui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Stark &amp; Sivec, 2009, 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. recurvata" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" rank="species" species="recurvata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">S. recurvata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Wu, 1938 and 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. ligula" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" rank="species" species="ligula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">S. ligula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Rehman, Huo &amp; Du, 2022 lack the tergum 9 transverse ridge similar to the new species and share some similar morphological characteristics with the new species. The head of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. wui" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" rank="species" species="wui">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">S. wui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bears a distinct triangular spot and the pronotum presents a dark median band (fig. 1 in 
<bibRefCitation author="Stark, B. P." journalOrPublisher="Illiesia" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" pagination="156 - 163" refId="B7871645" refString="Stark, B. P., Sivec, I., 2009. Sweltsa wui and Haploperla valentinae (Plecoptera: Chloroperlidae), two new stoneflies from Sichuan Province, China. Illiesia 5: 156 - 163" title="Sweltsa wui and Haploperla valentinae (Plecoptera: Chloroperlidae), two new stoneflies from Sichuan Province, China" volume="5" year="2009">Stark and Sivec 2009</bibRefCitation>
). In contrast, the head of the new species has a large rectangular median dark brown marking covering frons and ocellar areas (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F7871724" captionText="Figure 1. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. Male A head and pronotum; B terminalia dorsal view; C terminalia ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681195" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">1</figureCitation>
). The epiproct apex of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. wui" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" rank="species" species="wui">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">S. wui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bears a sclerotised cap, laterally much-expanded apically (figs. 6 and 7 in 
<bibRefCitation author="Stark, B. P." journalOrPublisher="Illiesia" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" pagination="156 - 163" refId="B7871645" refString="Stark, B. P., Sivec, I., 2009. Sweltsa wui and Haploperla valentinae (Plecoptera: Chloroperlidae), two new stoneflies from Sichuan Province, China. Illiesia 5: 156 - 163" title="Sweltsa wui and Haploperla valentinae (Plecoptera: Chloroperlidae), two new stoneflies from Sichuan Province, China" volume="5" year="2009">Stark and Sivec 2009</bibRefCitation>
), while the new species epiproct apex is swollen and lacks the cap and the lateral apex is slightly swollen upwards (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F7871728" captionText="Figure 2. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. Male A terminalia lateral view; B epiproct dorsal view; C epiproct lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681196" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">2</figureCitation>
A-C). Epiproct of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. recurvata" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" rank="species" species="recurvata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">S. recurvata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is elongate, dorsally and laterally almost parallel from base to apex, apex pointed and, dorsolaterally, the tip is pencil-shaped (figs. 187-188 in 
<bibRefCitation author="Wu, C. F." journalOrPublisher="Yenching University, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" refId="B7871681" refString="Wu, C. F., 1938. Plecopterorum sinensium: A monograph of the stoneflies of China (Order Plecoptera). Yenching University, Beijing" title="Plecopterorum sinensium: A monograph of the stoneflies of China (Order Plecoptera)" year="1938">Wu 1938</bibRefCitation>
), whereas the epiproct of the new species is much shorter, the apex is swollen like a bottle-cap and bent upwards in lateral view, easily differentiating the new species. The new species also show similar characteristics to 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. ligula" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" rank="species" species="ligula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">S. ligula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Rehman, Huo &amp; Du, 2022. The epiproct of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. ligula" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" rank="species" species="ligula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">S. ligula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is much larger and bears a spoon-shaped apex (figs. 1 and 3 in 
<bibRefCitation author="Rehman, Abdur" journalOrPublisher="Biodiversity Data Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" refId="B7871619" refString="Rehman, Abdur, Huo, Q. B, Du, Y. Z, 2022. A new species of the genus Sweltsa Ricker, 1943 (Plecoptera, Chloroperlidae) from Guizhou Province, China. Biodiversity Data Journal 10: e80433." title="A new species of the genus Sweltsa Ricker, 1943 (Plecoptera, Chloroperlidae) from Guizhou Province, China" volume="10: e 80433." year="2022">Rehman et al. 2022a</bibRefCitation>
), while the new species epiproct is short with a swollen apex. The female subgenital plate of the new species is similar to the 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. ligula" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" rank="species" species="ligula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">S. ligula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
female, but can be easily distinguished by the body structure and pigmentation. The new species posterior notch of the subgenital plate is broader and sides of the notch possess fine hairs (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F7871736" captionText="Figure 4. Sweltsa liupanshana Rehman, Du &amp; Huo sp. n. Female A head and pronotum; B terminalia ventral view; C subgenital plate." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681198" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">4</figureCitation>
C), while the 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. ligula" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" rank="species" species="ligula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">S. ligula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
plate is sclerotised and the posterior notch lacks hairs which easily distinguish these two females.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
